@DATABASE myGOLD.guide
@$VER: myGOLD.guide V0.1
@AUTHOR Christian T. Steigies
@(C)    Christian T. Steigies   steigies@physik.uni-kiel.de

@MASTER

@WIDTH 74

@NODE MAIN "MyGold"
@NEXT shortcut
This is an AmigaGuide® file made by @{" Christian T. Steigies. " LINK author}

My favorite editor is GoldED, but its not yet perfect the  way  you  get
it, you have to configure a bit to your needs. I have been defining some
shortcuts which I find very handy. Probably many other people have  made
something  similar,  but  I haven't found anything on the net (yet). I'm
going to write down my shortcuts, it would be very nice if some  of  you
could  tell me about the latest tricks and usages of the GoldED internal
commands. I'm quite lazy in reading long docs, I wanna use it!

As I use GED for writing C sources, TeX text, emails, ... I have defined
several  configs  which  are  designed for the special purpose (i.e. the
folder marks, WRAP and OVER mode, ...).

Here come my @{" shortcuts " LINK shortcut }


This guide was written with GoldED/Pro 3.1.3.

@ENDNODE

@NODE author "Christian T. Steigies"
@PREV main
@NEXT main
@TOC main

          Please send comments, ammendments and donations ;-) to:

                 steigies@physik.uni-kiel.de

         Thank you!

@ENDNODE

@NODE shortcut "shortcut"
@PREV main
@NEXT ctrl-a
@TOC main
Beginning of a line                     @{" CTRL-A " LINK ctrl-a }
End of a line                           @{" CTRL-E " LINK ctrl-e }
Transpose chars                         @{" CTRL-T " LINK ctrl-t }
Convert a character to UPPERcase        @{" CTRL-U " LINK ctrl-u }
Convert a character to LOWERcase        @{" CTRL-L " LINK ctrl-l }

@ENDNODE

@NODE ctrl-a "CTRL-A : Jump to the beginning of a line ('Anfang')"
@PREV shortcut
@NEXT ctrl-e
@TOC main
To go to the beginning of a line, DOS computers have an  extra  key  for
this purpose...

Definition with internal commands:
  GOTO COLUMN 1

@ENDNODE

@NODE ctrl-e "CTRL-E : Jump to the end of a line ('Ende')"
@PREV ctrl-a
@NEXT ctrl-t
@TOC main
To go to the end of a line, DOS computers have an  extra  key  for  this
purpose...

Definition with internal commands:
  GOTO EOL

@ENDNODE

@NODE ctrl-t "CTRL-T : Transpose chars"
@PREV ctrl-e
@NEXT ctrl-u
@TOC main
My favorite mistake when typing is to  transpose  two  characters.  That
means  I  write  'teh' instead of 'the'. With this shortcut (which I saw
implemented in another editor, whose name slipped my mind) its very easy
to correct this mistake. Just move the CURSOR on the second character of
the transposed chars (in this case the 'h') and press CTRL-T.

NOTICE: This one only works when you are  NOT  in  the  OVERwrite  mode.
Otherwise  the character left of the cursor is deleted. If I knew how to
check weather the editor is in the OVERwrite mode or not, this could  be
corrected.

Definition with internal commands:
  MARK HIDE
  MARK SET COLUMN
  LEFT
  BLOCK MOVE
  RIGHT

@ENDNODE

@NODE ctrl-u "CTRL-U : upper char"
@PREV ctrl-t
@NEXT ctrl-l
@TOC main
To change the character under the cursor to upper case

Definition with internal commands:
  MARK HIDE
  MARK SET COLUMN
  BLOCK UPPER
  BLOCK HIDE

@ENDNODE

@NODE ctrl-l "CTRL-L : lower char"
@PREV ctrl-u
@NEXT shortcut
@TOC main
To change the character under the cursor to lower case

Definition with internal commands:
  MARK HIDE
  MARK SET COLUMN
  BLOCK LOWER
  BLOCK HIDE

@ENDNODE



